<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson3_6" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Superposition in Qiskit</title>
  <p> Now that we've explored superposition in quantum computing, let's start building some of these
    circuits in Qiskit. As you probably expected, applying an <c>H</c> or <c>Z</c> gate to a qubit is
    just the same as any other 1-qubit gate (like <c>NOT</c>!). </p>

  <listing xml:id="h-z-gates">
    <title><c>H</c> and <c>Z</c> Gates in Qiskit</title>
    <program xml:id="h-z-gate-program" interactive="activecode" language="python3">
      <code>
          from qiskit import QuantumCircuit

          circuit1 = QuantumCircuit(2)
          circuit1.h(0)
          circuit1.z(0)
          circuit1.h(0)
          circuit1.x(1)
          circuit1.swap(0, 1)
          print(circuit1.draw())
        </code>
    </program>
  </listing>

  <p> Measuring a circuit with <c>H</c> and <c>Z</c> gates is much like measuring any other quantum
    circuit. However, as we've discussed before, to get a more accurate picture of a superposition
    state, we want to run the same circuit <em>many</em> times to try to glean the probabilities of
    achieving each outcome. We will explore how to actually run and measure these circuits in future
    chapters. For now, all we need to do is once again use the <c>measure_all()</c> function to make a
    measurement after applying our quantum gates.</p>

  <listing xml:id="superposition-measurement-qiskit">
    <title>Measuring Superposition States in Qiskit</title>
    <program xml:id="superposition-measurement-qiskit-program" interactive="activecode"
      language="python3">
      from qiskit import QuantumCircuit

      # Build our circuit
      circuit2 = QuantumCircuit(1)
      circuit2.h(0)
      circuit2.measure_all()

      print(circuit2.draw())
    </program>
  </listing>

